## Summary Table of Reaganomics Failures

| Failure Aspect                | Description                                                                                  | Impact                                                                                      |
|------------------------------|----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Income Inequality             | Wealth concentrated among top earners; middle class income stagnated or declined             | Widened wealth gap; middle class erosion                                                   |
| Tax Policy                   | Top tax cuts offset by middle-class tax increases                                            | Shifted tax burden; undermined equitable taxation                                         |
| Government Spending          | Military spending increased despite promises to cut spending                                | Budget deficits and national debt tripled                                                  |
| Savings and Loan Crisis      | Deregulation led to risky financial behavior and institutional failures                      | $160 billion taxpayer bailout; financial instability                                       |
| Job Quality                 | Job growth in low-paying, insecure jobs; decline in union power                             | Persistent poverty and wage stagnation                                                     |
| Supply-Side Assumptions      | Overestimated economic growth from tax cuts; wealthy saved or invested abroad               | Revenue shortfalls; budget deficits                                                        |
| Social Welfare Cuts          | Reduced government support for poor and vulnerable populations                              | Increased poverty rates; reduced social mobility                                          |

---

## Conclusion

Reaganomics, while credited with some macroeconomic improvements such as reduced inflation and short-term economic growth, ultimately failed in several critical areas. Its policies exacerbated income inequality, shifted tax burdens unfairly, failed to control government spending, and contributed to financial crises. The overreliance on supply-side assumptions and the neglect of job quality and social welfare further undermined its effectiveness.

The evidence suggests that Reaganomics did not deliver broad-based prosperity but instead favored the wealthy at the expense of the middle and lower classes. Its legacy is a more unequal society with persistent economic challenges that continue to influence American economic policy debates today.

